<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910220-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>910220-0044.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Justices Say They'll Rule   On Military Leave Requests</HL><DATE>02/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4</SO><GV>SUPREME COURT (SUP)EXECUTIVE (EXE)DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Supreme Court will decide when employersmust give workers leaves of absence for training oradministrative duty in the military reserves or statenational guards.   Although the issue touches a nerve with more than 200,000reservists in the Persian Gulf, the court's decision,expected next year, doesn't involve the section of federallaw used to deploy troops to Saudi Arabia. The case appliesonly to reserve or guard duty for training, organization andadministration.</LP><TEXT>   In the case of a hospital worker in Birmingham, Ala., afederal appeals court in Atlanta ruled in May 1990 that anemployer may deny a leave for military service that is&quot;unreasonable.&quot; The appeals court said the worker's requestfor a three-year leave to assume an administrative post inthe Alabama National Guard was unreasonable.   The Bush administration appealed to the high court toargue that federal law requires the re-employment of workerswho leave for military training and that there is norequirement that a worker's request for leave be reasonable.(King vs. St. Vincent's Hospital)</TEXT></DOC>